371":"1371","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1375":"about 1375","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston Castle, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":11,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Hulgreve was born in 1371, in Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Hulgreve, was 27 and her mother, Alice de Moston, was 21. She married John Beeston in 1389, in Tiverton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1420, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1371–1420":"1371–1420","1370–1420":"1370–1420","1395–1455":"1395–1455","1344–1375":"1344–1375","1350–1395":"1350–1395","Abt 1419":"umbes 1419","1389":"1389","1455":"1455","1344":"1344","1420":"1420","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","about 1375":"umbes 1375","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Inglis